Certainly, I can help you with that. Below is a sample PowerShell script that you can use to temporarily adjust Windows Defender and third-party AV service states via Group Policy Objects (GPO) in a SCCM-compliant configuration baseline.

```powershell
# Define the configuration data
$ConfigData = @{
    AllNodes = @(
        @{
            NodeName = 'localhost'
            PSDscAllowPlainTextPassword = $true
        }
    )
}

# Define the configuration
Configuration AdjustSecurityAgents {
    param (
        [Parameter(Mandatory)]
        [string]$DomainGPOName,
        [Parameter(Mandatory)]
        [string]$LegacyAppMaintenanceWindow
    )

    Import-DscResource -ModuleName 'PSDesiredStateConfiguration'

    Node $AllNodes.NodeName {
        # Disable Windows Defender
        Registry DisableWindowsDefender {
            Key = 'HKLM:\SOFTWARE\Policies\Microsoft\Windows Defender'
            ValueName = 'DisableAntiSpyware'
            ValueType = 'DWord'
            ValueData = 1
            Ensure = 'Present'
        }

        # Stop and disable third-party AV service
        Service StopThirdPartyAVService {
            Name = 'ThirdPartyAVServiceName'
            State = 'Stopped'
            StartupType = 'Disabled'
        }
    }
}

# Generate MOF file
AdjustSecurityAgents -DomainGPOName 'YourDomainGPOName' -LegacyAppMaintenanceWindow 'YourMaintenanceWindow' -ConfigurationData $ConfigData
AdjustSecurityAgents
Start-DscConfiguration -Path .\AdjustSecurityAgents -Wait -Verbose
```

Replace 'YourDomainGPOName' with the name of your domain GPO and 'YourMaintenanceWindow' with the name of your legacy application maintenance window. Also, replace 'ThirdPartyAVServiceName' with the actual name of the third-party AV service.

This script will generate a MOF file and apply the configuration to the target nodes. Make sure to test this script in a non-production environment before applying it to your enterprise environment.
